  "doc_id": "15097",
  "text": "In this paper we consider three classifier architectures (Table 2) , all of which are based on the \"C3D\" volumetric convolutional network proposed by Tran et al. [CITATION_1] . The first is a direct implementation of the C3D architecture which follows the original work closely. All layers up until and excluding the first fully connected layer form the model body, and the rest form a head. The second is an altered version of C3D which makes room for batch normalization (BN) [CITATION_2] by halving the number of features throughout the network. The third architecture introduces dilated convolutions for scale invariance [CITATION_3] . Pooling in the latter half of the body is removed, and the last two convolutional layers given a dilation of 2 (conv3-d2) to maintain receptive field size. A context network [CITATION_4] with layers 5 and 6 removed is introduced into the head for multi-scale aggregation.",
